comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text:
Early (mid to late 16th-century?) ms. inscription recording the gift of three books on Christmas Day from Lienhart Sedlmeier and Hans Hueben to Gerg Leuttel, a cleric (probably Catholic) in Engelbrechtsmünster (now part of Geisenfeld) and provost of "God's house" in Westenhausen (now part of Manching), both in Bavaria southeast of Ingolstadt. The books in question are:
Bentzius, Michael. Rettung Der wolgegründten vrsachen des abtrettens von den Secten, zu der alten wahren, recht Euangelischen Catholischen Kirchen (Munich: Adam Berg, 1569; VD 16 B 1745) a book of twelve sermons by Johannes Nas (possibly his twelve sermons on the Eucharist, of which two editions were printed in Ingolstadt by the Weissenhorns in 1568 and 1569, respectively) Rasperger, Christoph. Verantwortung, Die Communion einer gstalt betreffend, mit gründlicher widerlegung dreyer Lutherischer Streit vnd Lasterschrifften (Munich: Adam Berg, 1567; VD 16 R 334)

comment.author: 24982336@N04
comment.text:
All persons mentioned are catholic for sure, as Bavaria was a centre of counter-reformation. And all three authors mentioned  - especially Johannes Nas - were definite leaders of the catholic counter-reformation.

The date of the inscription should be shortly after the publication of the books in question -- the early 1570s

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text: Woodcut arms probably to be associated with the principality of Braunschweig-Lüneburg-Wolffenbüttel. The work in which it appears contains a "Fürstliche Braunschweigische Hoffgerichts Ordnung"; various elements of the whole are present in the arms of Braunschweig-Lüneburg, and Wolffenbüttel. The initials "G.V.M.G." at head stand for "Gottes Versehen muss geschehen" ("God's providence must happen"), a motto which appears on (among other things) the coinage of Julius, Duke of Braunschweig-Lüneburg (1528-1589). Cf. this coin from Julius's reign, which includes the above arms on its reverse. Used by Conrad Horn of Wolfenbüttel. Established heading: Horn, Conrad, ‡d fl. 1565-1603

comment.text:
Armorial Bookplate of Le Gendre Pierce Starkie (Patriae Amicisque Fidelis)

Likely Le Gendre Pierce Starkie (1760-1807) of Huntroyd (Lancashire, United Kingdom) or perhaps his son of the same name (1796-1819). Neither established.  See ESTC N30152 for identical bookplate at the Folger.

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text: This website on the Starkie family gives "Le Gendre Piers Starkie" for the elder (1760-1807) and "Le Gendre Pierce Starkie" for the younger (1796-1819). Eighteenth- and nineteenth-century orthography is not an exact science, of course. But the book in which this plate appears (Abraham and Gottfried Bucholzer's Index Chronologicus) was purchased by the Penn Libraries in 1962, the same year the library of Guy Piers Le Gendre Starkie was sold by Sotheby's. At this sale the Huntington Library purchased a 14th-century Mariale ms. with the "[b]ookplate of Le Gendre Pierce Starkie (b. 1796)" that is known to have been owned by Richard Wroe. Penn's Index Chronologicus has Richard Wroe's autograph on the title leaf as well as this Starkie bookplate. Assuming the Huntington knows its stuff, I'm inclined to identify this plate as that of Starkie the younger.

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text: Jakob Reutlinger (1545-1611) was born in Überlingen, Germany (on the north shore of the Bodensee/Lake Constance). He was the son of Josef Reutlinger, a guildmaster (possibly of the shoemaker's guild, since Jakob later held that position). He attended the Latin school in Überlingen and was also tutored by Veit Spon, the city's notary (Stadtschreiber). In 1568 he married Ursula Ungemuet by whom he had eight children (3 sons and 5 daughters). Beginning in 1576 he held various city offices, eventually rising to Bürgermeister in 1600, in which position he served until his death from plague in 1611. He was a skilled diplomat and frequent traveler, often purchasing books for the Ratsbibliothek while abroad (the receipts are still held in the city archives; cf. Handbuch der historischen Buchbestände in Deutschland (Hildesheim: Ohms, 1992-2000), Bd. 9, p. 140). Reutlinger is best known for the "chronicle" of noteworthy events -- personal, social and political -- which he began writing in 1580; the manuscript had reached 16 volumes by the time he died. For biographical notes as well as a summary of Reutlinger's work, see R.W. Brednich, "Das Reutlingersche Sammelwerk im Stadtarchiv Überlingen als volkskundliche Quelle" in Jahrbuch für Volksliedforschung 10. Jahrg. (1965), p. 42-84. DNB heading: Reutlinger, Jakob, ‡d 1545-1611

Written out on the titlepage: an epigram of Ausonius

Owen Feltham (1602-1668) translates this as follows:

When the tubbed Cynic went to hell, and there 
Found the pale ghost of golden Croesus bare, 
He stops, and jeering tilt he shrugs again, 
Says; O thou richest king of kings, what gain 
Have all thy large heaps brought thee, since I spy 
Thee here alone, and poorer now than I? 
For, all I had, I with me bring: but thou, 
Of all thy wealth, hast not one farthing now.

comment.author: 58592597@N05
comment.text: Unidentified ms. signatures on title page of "Richardus Whyt" with "Richardus" crossed out and "William" [Whyt]" added below. According to the bookseller's note mounted on front pastedown of this book "Richardus Whyt" was probably either the 16th c. Catholic martyr and Welsh schoolmaster Gwyn, Richard,‏ ‎ Saint,‏ ‎1537-1584‏ [also known by his anglicized name Richard White] or the 16th c. jurist/historian and professor of law at Douai (where this book was published). White, Richard, 1539-1611 According to dealer's note the book has "Oxford binding" with centerpiece "xvi" as identified by Neil Ker in "Oxford bookbinding, 1500-1640". Note concludes that given this book's Oxford binding and the ms. annotations from Aelius Donatus "Ars gramattica" and quotation from Seneca on front flyleaf, the owner was more likely to have been Richard White the Catholic martyr. Cf. DNB entries for Richard White (ca. 1537-1584) www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/29264?docPos=1 and Richard White (1539-1611) www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/29265?docPos=3 Provenance remains unclear. Richard White the martyr did attend Oxford briefly, wrote poetry and had a son by the name of William so this attribution is certainly a good possibility. Could also be a later 17th c. owner with the same name as in ‏ White, Richard,‏ ‎b. 1636 or none of the above.
